The '''Austrian State Prize for European Literature''' ({{lang-de|Österreichischer Staatspreis für Europäische Literatur}}), also known in Austria as the '''European Literary Award''' (''Europäischer Literaturpreis''), is an [[Austria]]n literary prize awarded by the Federal Chancellery for Arts, Culture, and Media to European writers.<ref name="oesterreich-bibliotheken">[https://archive.is/20120529161211/http://www.oesterreich-bibliotheken.at/preistraegerinnen.php?preis=preise_euliteratur Österreichische StaatspreisträgerInnen für Europäische Literatur] {{de icon}}. Last accessed: September 20, 2016.</ref><ref name="kunstkultur.bka.gv.at">[http://www.kunstkultur.bka.gv.at/site/8112/default.aspx Österreichischer Staatspreis für Europäische Literatur] {{de icon}}. Last accessed: September 20, 2016.</ref> Established in 1965, the prize is endowed with a purse of 25,000 € (2016).<ref name="Andrzej Stasiuk">[https://www.bka.gv.at/site/cob__63451/currentpage__0/6592/default.aspx Kulturminister Drozda zeichnet Andrzej Stasiuk aus]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{de icon}} on 2016 prizewinner Andrzej Stasiuk. Last accessed: September 20, 2016.</ref> The prize was not awarded in 1969.

==List of winners==
<!--Note: The list at ref www.oesterreich-bibliotheken.at and elsewhere is taken to be inaccurate and the list at ref "www.kunstkultur.bka.gv.at" as accurate, as the latter cross-references with [http://www.bildarchivaustria.at/Pages/ImageDetail.aspx?p_iBildID=14942003] and [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=SzgFAQAAIAAJ&q="Lem+(1985)"&]. The former source lists Austrian Ilse Aichinger (who as an Austrian didn't win this international prize but won the 1995 Preisträgerinnen und Preisträger Literatur instead), jumbles the order of awards, and omits three winners: 1975's Miroslav Krleža, 1986's Giorgio Manganelli, and 1999's Péter Esterházy.--> 
