{{Culture of Algeria}}
{{Refimprove|date=August 2009}}

'''''Nuubaat''''' ({{lang-ar|'''نوبات'''}} {{IPA-ar|nuːˈbæːt|}}) is a form of [[Algeria]]n [[classical music]]. The term itself is the [[plural]] form of ''nūba'' (نوبة), a [[suite (music)|suite]] of old [[Al-Andalus|Andalusian]] musical pieces. It is these multi-[[movement (music)|movement]] works that give nuubaat its name. The music originally spread from [[Islamic]] [[Spain]] to [[North Africa]] following the [[Christian]] [[Reconquista|Reconquest]] of Spain and subsequent [[Alhambra decree|expulsion]] of [[Sephardic Jews]] and [[Muslims]]. In Algeria, the form originally found a home in the cities of [[Constantine, Algeria|Constantine]] and [[Tlemcen]], with [[Algiers]] later becoming an influential center as well.<ref name=Reynolds>{{cite journal|last=Reynolds |first=Dwight |date=July 1995 |title=Music of Algeria: Selected Recordings |journal=Middle East Studies Association Bulletin |volume=29 |issue=1 |pages=16–21 |issn=0026-3184 |url=http://fp.arizona.edu/mesassoc/Bulletin/reynolds.htm |accessdate=2013-06-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606160854/http://fp.arizona.edu/mesassoc/Bulletin/reynolds.htm |archivedate=June 6, 2011 }}</ref>

